{"cursor":"10621","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n, Scotland, is stopped by an overlying layer of warmer air (2006).]] In\nmeteorology, an 'inversion' is a deviation from the normal change of an\natmospheric property with altitude. It almost always refers to a \"temperature\ninversion\", i.e., an increase in temperature with height, or to the layer\n(\"inversion layer\") within which such an increase occurs. Database\n(undated). [http://www.nws.noaa.gov/glossary/index.php?letter=i \"Here Are the\nResults for the Letter I\"]. National Weather Service. Retrieved July 14,\n2012.\n\nAn inversion can lead to pollution such as smog being trapped close to the\nground, with possible adverse effects on health. An inversion can also suppress\nconvection by acting as a \"cap\". If this cap is broken for any of several\nreasons, convection of any moisture present can then erupt into violent\nthunderstorms. Temperature inversion can notoriously result in freezing rain in\ncold climates.\n","linknr":282,"url":"Temperature_inversion","recorded":1362540658,"links":57,"instances":["mirage","telecommunication","electronics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Atmospheric thermodynamics","Radio frequency propagation"],"headings":["Normal atmospheric conditions","How and why inversions occur","Subsidence inversion","Consequences of a thermal inversion","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/SmokeCeilingInLochcarron.jpg/220px-SmokeCeilingInLochcarron.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/03/Absinkinversion.png/220px-Absinkinversion.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//u